Blocks.childText: HYMNS. 4 And I have brought to thee, Give every flying minute Down from my home above, Something to keep in store; Salvation full and free, Work, for the night is coming, My pardon and My love When man works no more. I bring, I bring rich gifts to thee, 3 Work, for the night is coming, What hast thou brought to me Under the sunset skies While their bright tints are glow- No. 189. ing, 1 Grace ! 'tis a charming sound, Work, for the daylight flies. Work, till the last beam fadeth, Harmonious to the ear : Fadeth to shine no more; Heaven with the echo shall re- sound, Work, while the night is darken- And all the earth shall hear. ing, When man's work is o'er. 2 Grace first contrived the way No. 191. To save rebellious man; And all the steps that grace dis- 1 Thou dear Redeemer,dying Lamb, I love to hear of Thee play Which drew the wondrous plan. No music's like Thy charming name, 3 Grace led my roving feet Nor half SO sweet can be. To tread the heavenly road; 2 O, let me ever hear Thy voice, And new supplies each hour I In mercy to me speak ; meet, In Thee, my Priest, will I rejoice, While pressing on to God. Thou great Melchisedec 4 Grace all the work shall crown, 3 My Jesus, shall be still my theme, Through everlasting days While in the world I stay It lays in heaven the topmost I'll sing my Jesus' lovely name, stone, When all things else decay. And well deserves the praise. 4 When I appear in yonder cloud, With all the favored throng, No. 190. Then will I sing more sweet, 1 Work, for the night is coming, more loud, Work through the morning And Christ shall be my song. JOHN CENNICK, 1745, a. hours No. 192. Work, while the dew is sparkling, C. M. Work 'mid springing flowers; 1 God moves in a mysterious way, Work, when the day grows His wonders to perform : brighter, He plants His footsteps in the sea, Work in the glowing sun ; And rides upon the storm. Work, for the night is coming, 2 Ye fearful saints, fresh courage When man's work is done. take ; 2 Work, for the night is coming, The clouds ye so much dread Work through the sunny noon : Are big with mercy, and shall Fill brightest hours with labor, break Rest comes sure and soon. With blessing on your head. 150
